section.section:
Every application for registration shall be on a form prepared by the Commission and shall provide such information as may be reasonably required by the Commission. The developer shall file with the Commission the following documents and information:
Copies of all project instruments and time-share instruments;
A copy of the proposed public offering statement which shall be supplemented by the public offering statement as finally approved by the Secretary of State;
Copies of the forms of the deed, sales contract, and all other written materials to be used in the normal course of the sale of the time-shares;
Evidence that time-share use complies with the zoning laws of the municipality in which the time-share project is located;
If the time-share units are subject to any project instrument, evidence that the project instruments do not prohibit the use of units for time-sharing purposes and, if the project instruments do not expressly authorize time-share use, a copy of a letter to the president of the governing entity of the project stating the developer's intent to use units for time-share purposes, together with evidence of its receipt by the addressee; and
The name and address of any project broker.

A registration application may not be approved until the applicant has:
Executed an irrevocable appointment of the Commission to receive service of process in any legal proceeding brought against the applicant arising out of the sale of time-share estates in this State provided that a duplicate copy of all papers regarding the applicant filed with the Commission is sent to the applicant at its last known address within 5 days thereafter;
Paid a registration fee of $100;
Provided the Commission with a list of the time-share estates and licenses to be offered and the name of the licensed broker of record representing the developer; and
Posted with the Commission a surety bond or letter of credit in an amount of $100,000 issued by an issuer and in a form acceptable to the Commission conditioned on the return of all money paid by a purchaser in the event the purchaser becomes entitled to the return of the money.

text.section:
The Commission, after notice and hearing, may issue an order revoking a registration upon determination that a developer has:
Failed to comply with a cease and desist order issued by the Commission;
Concealed, diverted, or disposed of any funds or assets of any person in a manner impairing rights of purchasers of those time-shares;
Failed to perform any stipulation or agreement made to induce the Commission to issue an order relating to those time-shares;
Misrepresented or failed to disclose a material fact in the application for registration;
Failed to meet any of the requirements for registration;
Violated any provisions of this title; or
Committed an unfair or deceptive trade practice.

section.section:
In determining the amount of the penalty, the Commission shall give due consideration to:
The seriousness of the violation;
The lack of good faith on the part of the developer;
The adverse impact, if any, on other persons;
Any efforts made by the developer to remedy or correct the violation; and
The developer's history of prior violations, particularly violations of the same or similar nature.

A judgment shall be entered against the developer upon a showing that:
The penalty was assessed against the developer;
The penalty has become final;
No appeal is pending;
The penalty remains unpaid in whole or part; and
The developer contested the charge for which the penalty was assessed, or was duly served with a copy of the charge under any applicable rules and regulations of the Commission.
